== Drive Parry ==
[[File:SF6_drive_parry.jpg|thumb|250px|"Automatically repel an opponent’s attack and replenish Drive when performed successfully. Perform a Perfect Parry by parrying just before an opponent’s attack hits you." - ''Capcom.'']]
'''Consumes ~1/2 Drive gauge upon activation, continues draining while held.''' Hold {{mp sf6}}+{{mk sf6}} ({{clr|M|MP}}+{{clr|M|MK}}) to perform. Becomes a '''Perfect Parry''' if it successfully parries an attack within 2 frames of being input '''(while holding the correct block direction for strikes)'''.
{| class="wikitable"
! St !! Act !! Rec 
|- style="text-align: center"
| 1 || 12~ [2] || 33 [1] 
|}
<small>''Note: [] refers to Perfect Parry''</small>
<br><br>

=== Regular Parry ===
'''Active Effects:'''
* Active for 12f before entering recovery; active period can be extended by holding Parry
* Parries all strikes and projectiles (from any direction) starting on frame 1
* Successful parry results in the same frame advantage as blocking the move
* Parry '''recovery''' lasts 33f after releasing the buttons
** Can still block during this time, but cannot perform any other action
** Also enters recovery immediately if the Drive cost causes a Burnout state
* Parry blockstun can be canceled into '''{{clr|DR|Drive Reversal}}'''
* From active frame 3 onward, Parry is cancelable into '''{{clr|DR|Drive Rush}}''' using a Forward Dash input (66)
** Often referred to as "{{clr|DR|Parry Drive Rush}} (PDR)", "{{clr|DR|Raw Drive Rush}}", "{{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} in neutral"
** To input more quickly from neutral, input as '''6, 6+{{clr|M|MP}}+{{clr|M|MK}}''' (Forward Dash with a Parry timed simultaneously with the 2nd forward input)
** After holding a successful Parry, {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} can be input immediately after Parry blockstun ends; useful for punishing some moves like Blanka Ball
** Parry cannot be canceled into {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} if the initial activation causes a Burnout state
<br><br>

'''Drive Cost/Gain:'''
* Costs 5000 Drive gauge upon activation (occurs on frame 2), plus 50 per frame starting on frame 4
** Minimum cost of 5450 for a whiffed parry (5000 + 50/frame on active frames 4-12)
* Awards 5000 Drive (1/2 bar) for parrying a Projectile (except Super Art projectiles)
** This essentially means the defender breaks even, rather than losing Drive meter for blocking the projectile
* Awards 10000 Drive (1 bar) for parrying a Normal, Special Move, or Drive Reversal
** Target Combos or Rekka strings (e.g. Jamie 236P~6P~6P) are considered separate attacks, so they award 10000 Drive per hit
* Awards 20000 Drive (2 bars) for parrying a Super Art, Critical Art, or Drive Impact
** This makes it significantly better than blocking, unless attempting a Parry would cause Burnout
** It's important to practice holding Parry on reaction to the opponent's Super freeze, and to learn how the Super connects vs. Parry (number of hits, pushback, blockstring gaps, etc.)
* Multi-hit attacks usually split the Drive gain between each hit, so you won't build extra meter when parrying them
* The opponent also builds some Drive gauge for having their attack parried, the same as if the attack was blocked
* Awards an extra 3000 Drive (30% bar) against strikes with '''Perfect Parry timing''' but '''no screen freeze''' (not holding the correct block direction)
** Does not apply to any follow-up hits in the same blockstring, and awards the same amount regardless of the strike's usual meter gain
<br><br>

'''Countering Parry:'''
* Throws (including Command Throws) hit as a {{clr|PC|Punish Counter}}, dealing high damage and draining 1 Drive bar
** This applies to all active and recovery frames of the Parry; the throw cannot be escaped
* Mixing between Low strikes and High/Mid strikes makes it harder for the opponent to Perfect Parry, making your pressure less risky
* Parry recovery does not automatically block, so left/right or high/low mixups can be applied
* The opponent's strike and throw hurtbox expands when using Parry, making them easier to hit
* Drive Impact connecting during Parry recovery can lead to an unavoidable wall splat
* Switching between fast and slow projectiles makes it harder for the opponent to time the Parry
** May input too late, or waste Drive gauge by inputting too early
* Using a limited-range projectile (Luke {{clr|L|LP}}/{{clr|M|MP}} Sand Blast, Chun-Li {{clr|L|LP Kikoken}}) just outside its range may bait the opponent into whiffing Parry and wasting Drive meter
<br><br>

'''Pushback Differences (compared to Blocking)'''
* Projectiles cause 1/2 the usual pushback distance
* Drive Impact has dramatically lower pushback, with no stagger animation or wall splat
* The pushback on Strikes is evenly distributed between both characters, rather than just pushing back the defender
** If one character is cornered, all pushback will be transferred to the non-cornered character
<br><br>

=== Perfect Parry ===
* Occurs only on the first 2 Parry active frames
* Perfect Parry '''cannot be buffered''' by holding the buttons (must be timed properly)
* Attempting a Perfect Parry with under 1/2 a Drive bar requires frame-perfect timing (will enter Burnout on frame 2 of parry)
** This may be required to survive against a corner {{clr|DR|Drive Impact}} if you do not have enough HP to absorb it with your counter-{{clr|DR|DI}}
* In general, Perfect Parry rewards the same amount of Drive gauge as a regular Parry
** In some cases, the invincibility of Perfect Parry causes some hits to whiff, which may reduce the total Drive gain
* A '''50% damage scaling multiplier''' is applied to any punish after a Perfect Parry (including vs. projectiles)
** Delaying your punish, or Perfect Parrying only the first hit of a multi-hit move, does not change this; you cannot avoid the scaling on a true punish
** Because of this harsh scaling, it may be worth optimizing the punish for screen position or Drive Gauge damage instead (e.g. {{clr|H|Heavy Normal}} > {{clr|DR|Drive Impact}} to drain ~2 bars)
* '''Meter Scaling:'''
** Both characters build 20% less {{clr|SA|Super}} gauge for all hits after a Perfect Parry
** The attacker builds 50% less Drive gauge and the defender takes 50% less Drive Damage after a Perfect Parry 
<br><br>

'''vs. Strikes:'''
* A successful Perfect Parry causes a zoomed-in '''screen freeze''', giving 60f (1 second) to react with a punish
* The correct block direction must be held to get this screen freeze: Down+Back for Low attacks, Back for High/Mid attacks
** Failing to hold the correct block direction results in a regular parry with enhanced Drive meter gain (often referred to by the community as "Imperfect Parry")
* The screen freeze has only 1f recovery, and prevents the opponent from canceling their attack in any way (Target Combo, Special, {{clr|SA|Super}}, {{clr|DR|Drive Impact}}, etc.)
* During the freeze, you can buffer any attack by holding the button; this ensures it will come out at the earliest possible timing
* Multi-hit moves like Jamie {{clr|H|5HP}} or Lily {{clr|10|Windclad 236KK}} still play out their remaining active frames after being Perfect Parried
* Perfect Parrying a deep jump-in does not always guarantee a punish; can be as safe as {{sf6-adv|M|-2}} at the latest possible timing
** Similarly, some fast light attacks are safer than usual (~{{sf6-adv|VM|-7}}); alternative punish combos may be required against these moves
* '''Fully invincible for 6f''' after screen freeze; this carries through any buffered attack
** This ensures that an attack 5f or faster will successfully punish the opponent, even if their attack has more active frames remaining
<br><br>

'''vs. Projectiles:'''
* A block direction is not required to Perfect Parry a projectile 
* Some '''pseudo-projectile''' moves allow a PP screen freeze and therefore still require a block direction, such as:
** AKI [[Street_Fighter_6/A.K.I.#Serpent_Lash_(236P)|Serpent Lash]] / [[Street_Fighter_6/A.K.I.#Nightshade_Chaser_(214LP~6P)|Nightshade Chaser]]
** Dhalsim [[Street_Fighter_6/Dhalsim#Yoga_Blast_(63214K)|Yoga Blast]]
** JP [[Street_Fighter_6/JP#Stribog_(236P)|Stribog]] (both hits) / [[Street_Fighter_6/JP#Level_1_Super_(236236P)|{{clr|SA|SA1}}]] (1st hit)
** Mai [[Street_Fighter_6/Mai#Ryuuenbu_(214P)|Ryuuenbu]]
** Rashid [[Street_Fighter_6/Rashid#Arabian_Cyclone_(214P)|Arabian Cyclone]]
** Ryu [[Street_Fighter_6/Ryu#Hashogeki_(214P)|Hashogeki]] / [[Street_Fighter_6/Ryu#Level_2_Super_(214214P)|{{clr|SA|SA2}}]]
** Terry [[Street_Fighter_6/Terry#Round_Wave_(236HP)|Round Wave]] (requires crouching PP)
* There is no screen freeze when Perfect Parrying a projectile; instead, it causes a fixed 11f recovery (1f Parry + 10f extra recovery)
* During this 11f recovery, characters are Throw invincible, and any further strikes will be automatically parried
* If a multi-hit projectile is Perfect Parried, it will freeze for those 11f, meaning you need to time/delay your next Parry input accordingly if you want to Perfect Parry the next hit of the projectile
* You can hold the Parry input up to 13 additional frames without incurring the standard 29f parry recovery afterward
* Buffering an immediate {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} allows for projectile punishes at midscreen against many characters
** This is less useful against slow projectiles, as the opponent will likely recover before it even makes contact
* Perfect Parrying a simultaneous strike + projectile combines the effects of both
** The screen freeze of a strike occurs, but results in 11f recovery like a projectile
<br><br>

