<br>

{{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} '''({{clr|DR|DR}})''' begins with a green flash of light and a 10-frame screen freeze, followed by a quick dash across the screen. Any Normal or Command Normal used during this dash gains '''+4''' advantage on Hit or Block, making it useful in a variety of offensive situations. They may also have [[Street_Fighter_6/Glossary#Juggles|improved juggle properties]], allowing for long extended juggle sequences. The {{clr|DR|DR}} dash can be canceled early by any attack while maintaining the forward momentum, allowing the user to stay close for tick throws, blockstrings, and combo extensions. 

The initial screen freeze gives the user extra time to confirm the opponent's status and decide on the next action. At the same time, the defender has more time to react to a raw {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} in neutral, or punish a blocked {{clr|DR|DR}} cancel with Drive Reversal. During this freeze, the defender's attacks, dashes, and jumps will be buffered. If multiple moves are input during the freeze, the one with higher priority will come out (e.g. {{clr|L|LP}}+{{clr|M|MP}}+{{clr|H|HP}} will give {{clr|H|HP}}, and {{clr|M|2MK}} > Hadoken will do just a reversal Hadoken). Another side effect is that a buffered neutral jump turns into a diagonal jump if Up is followed by Forward or Back during the freeze.

When {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} is used mid-combo, an extra 15% damage scaling penalty applies (multiplied by any other existing damage scaling); this only applies once per combo, and does not occur when ''beginning'' a combo with {{clr|DR|Parry Drive Rush}} into an enhanced normal. When this scaling occurs, you are locked out of passive Drive Gauge regeneration until the combo ends; however, you can still build some Drive by walking forward mid-combo, and entering the cinematic of a {{clr|SA|Level 3 Super}} will restart the Drive regeneration.

After the initial startup frames, there are 15 recovery frames that can be canceled only into attacks, followed by 22 more frames that are fully cancelable into any attack or movement option like crouch, block, or jump. This makes {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} a somewhat committal offensive tool at closer ranges, as you can't simply defend mid-dash while observing the opponent's response. Note that you cannot cancel any part of {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} into a Parry, as {{clr|M|MK}} will come out instead.

'''Additionally, any hit that connects during the {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} movement frames is considered a {{clr|PC|Counter Hit}}, including Throws (which prevents a Throw Escape from occurring once it connects).'''

To safely bait a 6-frame reversal out of {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}}, you must have a Knockdown Advantage of at least +21 in order to block. By whiffing a fast light normal, you may be able to bait a reversal at only KD +18~20, though this leaves you unsafe if the opponent doesn't take the bait. It's also possible to bait some reversals by stopping short with a whiffed throw, causing the opponent to whiff, though this highly context-dependent.

When canceling {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} into a directional movement (walk/crouch/block/jump), it will play out 2 additional recovery frames before the transition occurs. To use a crouching normal or command normal late in the {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} animation, you must input the direction + button nearly simultaneously, otherwise the {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} status will end and the normal will not receive the +4 bonus advantage.

Any special-cancelable normal can be canceled into the 3-bar {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} when it makes contact with the opponent. Light normals are also cancelable on whiff, which prevents them from being used as a low-risk buffer in neutral. The cancel window of a whiffed light normal is extended so that it is impossible to create an option select that only gives {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} on hit/block but not on whiff. 

Because a raw {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} begins with a Parry, it cannot be performed with under 1/2 a Drive bar. The initial cost of the Parry drains your gauge immediately and puts you into Burnout before the {{clr|DR|DR}} cancel window occurs. This limitation does not apply to the 3-bar {{clr|DR|Drive Rush}} cancels. This allows you to use a whiffed light into {{clr|DR|DR}} in neutral as though it were a {{clr|DR|Parry Drive Rush}}. In late-game situations where it would be difficult to avoid Burnout, this can be a useful strategy to force one last mixup to secure the win.


