== Super Gauge ==
The {{clr|SA|Super}} Gauge is only used to perform {{clr|SA|Super Arts}}. Characters gain {{clr|SA|Super}} meter when an attack connects on hit or block, or when a Throw Escape is performed; unlike in many previous games, no meter is built for whiffing an attack. Both players start the match with an empty {{clr|SA|Super}} Gauge, and can build up to 3 bars total. The {{clr|SA|Super}} meter carries over between rounds, so there is more to consider when deciding whether or not to spend meter to finish a round.


As a general rule, {{clr|SA|Super}} Gauge build on hit/block works as follows:
{| class="wikitable"
! !! on Hit !! on Block !! on Armor Absorb
|-
! Attacker
| (Base) || 50% || (Base)
|-
! Defender
| 70% || 25% || 35%
|}


The amount of {{clr|SA|Super}} Gauge built from an attack is not affected by {{clr|PC|Counter-hit}} or {{clr|PC|Punish Counter}} status (except for Throws), and is also not subject to combo scaling. {{clr|DR|Drive Impact}}, Drive Reversal, and {{clr|SA|Super Arts}} do not build additional {{clr|SA|Super}} Gauge for the attacker or defender, although any followup combo can still build meter. A few {{clr|SA|Super Arts}} that allow follow-up hits, such as Rashid's or Ed's {{clr|SA|SA2}}, will scale the meter gain on any additional hits in the combo to make it harder to immediately rebuild another full bar.

<br><br>

=== Super Art ===
A {{clr|SA|Super Art}} is essentially a more powerful type of Special move, requiring Super meter and a more complex input. In addition to damage, Supers often have improved properties like armor break, invincibility, juggle potential. Some Level 2 Super Arts are not attacks, but a powerup like Juri's Feng Shui Engine; this is known as an "install" Super. Install Supers turn the meter into a timer that ticks down until empty, at which point the character returns to normal. When a character is under 25% health, their Level 3 Super turns into a "Critical Art", which deals a bit more damage and may change the knockdown advantage/spacing afterwards.


Canceling an attack into a Super Art works differently than other moves:
* {{clr|SA|Lv.1 Super}} ({{clr|SA|SA1}}) can be canceled from Normals only
* {{clr|SA|Lv.2 Super}} ({{clr|SA|SA2}}) can be canceled from Normals and {{clr|OD|OD}} Specials
* {{clr|SA|Lv.3 Super/Critical Art}} ({{clr|SA|SA3/CA}}) can be canceled from Normals and Specials
** ''Not all Normals and Specials are cancelable into {{clr|SA|Super Arts}}; refer to the "cancel" column in the move's frame data''


{{clr|SA|Super Arts}} are an important tool for Drive Gauge management; they can drain the opponent's Drive Gauge and prevent passive regeneration, while using the time to allow your own gauge to passively recover. You can stall for time to prevent Burnout, or ensure the opponent enters Burnout after they overextend in their Drive Gauge usage. During Burnout, invincible {{clr|SA|Supers}} are the primary way to avoid being stunned by corner {{clr|DR|Drive Impact}} blockstrings, which would otherwise be unavoidable after blocking a cancelable heavy normal.

The round timer is frozen for the entire duration of a {{clr|SA|Super Art}} (except for install Supers that allow the character to act independently). This means that as long as you activate the {{clr|SA|Super}} before time expires, you're guaranteed to get the full damage (or chip damage vs. Burnout) without having to worry about the length of the animation.

